        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"African American Culinary Heroes: John Meyer of BJ&#039;s Market";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:109:"http://www.chicagonow.com/vociferous-envoy/2016/02/african-american-culinary-heroes-john-meyer-of-bjs-market/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:118:"http://www.chicagonow.com/vociferous-envoy/2016/02/african-american-culinary-heroes-john-meyer-of-bjs-market/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 11 Feb 2016 06:05:55 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://www.chicagonow.com/vociferous-envoy/?p=1485";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3740:"I first heard about John Meyer in the early 1990’s when he ran an upscale restaurant in one of the Pullman mansions on the far southeast side. We had my grandparents wedding anniversary there around 1993 &amp; 1994 and dined there a few other times.

The place was called The Retreat and it was a serious white table cloth establishment, a rarity even in Pullman but definitely not seen on the south side of Chicago. It was more than a “retreat” it was refreshing to have a “grown folks restaurant” so close to home.

John is a Chicago guy who attended Chicago State University and had his culinary studies at Washburne trade school. He also worked at the University Club in Hyde Park before striking out on his own.

John’s next and current venture is BJ’s Market, a casual yet very good soul food restaurant. It has a buffet but the servers fill your plate or to go box.

John doesn’t skimp on the soul but makes it healthier, he makes killer collard greens but has turkey in them. He inspired me to put turkey in my collards when I make them at home.
But his mustard fried catfish is the star dish.

BJ’s first location is on Stony Island just south of 87th Street, they have Sunday brunch and serve breakfast as well as lunch and dinner.

He then had a location for a while in Beverly on Western around 97th Street, it’s since closed. I lived there, that was my after church spot when I lived in the city and often after work dinner.

If had to go to Little Company of Mary Hospital to check on a relative or do business on 95th Street, I had to go and get me some catfish and greens from BJ’s.

He also has another location in Gresham on 79th, just east of Racine near St Sabina’s.

John also does catering I hear from the Stony Island BJ’s location.

I had learned from another restaurant and my former co-workers in south suburban Matteson that some people put mustard on their catfish as a condiment. Let me tell you that’s an intoxicating way to have your catfish.
John took it a step further and has it in the mix when he cooks the catfish. People come from far and wide to get John’s catfish.

Don’t believe me, go to Taste of Chicago this summer (BJ’s market has been participating for at least 15 years), and you will find long lines of people to get an order of catfish. Yes I am one of those people standing in line waiting. Last year I first got a “taste size” order of catfish and then before I left I used the last of my tickets to get more.

But John’s fish was so popular that they ran out. Literally so many people came for catfish that they ate all of the fish and the workers had to go get more and said it was a 30 minute wait. I’ve never seen so many people “bummed out” over a restaurant selling out of food.

When it was announced that they ran out of catfish, there was a “collective groan” from the lines of people and we all walked away slowly and disappointed.

But that’s just a testament to John and the quality of food at his restaurants, never had a bad meal there, always good staff and took many friends and family to enjoy his food.

John is a culinary hero for his commitment to the neighborhoods and his excellent food.

