        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"African American Culinary Heroes: Charlie Taylor of The Gulfport Cafe";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:120:"http://www.chicagonow.com/vociferous-envoy/2016/02/african-american-culinary-heroes-charlie-taylor-of-the-gulfport-cafe/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:129:"http://www.chicagonow.com/vociferous-envoy/2016/02/african-american-culinary-heroes-charlie-taylor-of-the-gulfport-cafe/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 08 Feb 2016 21:47:49 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://www.chicagonow.com/vociferous-envoy/?p=1481";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4309:"One of my heroes was our local restaurant chef, his name was Chef Charlie Taylor. I grew up on the end of West Pullman on 123rd Street and right at 124th &amp; Ashland was the Gulfport Café.

When it opened in 1983 my life changed forever, I believe it was a former truck stop or diner (we never went there), but once the Gulfport opened we lived there.

Chef Taylor came from the top rated L ’Escargot restaurant in downtown Chicago and he was their sous chef. He brought his maître ’d with him and they co-owned the new restaurant.

You talk about following a dream, Chef Taylor left the established, highly rated kitchen at one of the best restaurants in Chicago, started a small independent southern/Cajun restaurant in a racially changing residential suburb bordering the end of Chicago.

And do all that and still be recognized as a great chef &amp; entrepreneur in the press and admired by us locals.

Though my grandparents came from Louisiana &amp; Texas, and even as a young child I knew about a lot of southern foods, my palate was groomed at the Gulfport.

The Gulfport Café got its name from the hometown of Chef Taylor and he did his hometown proud. He started as a chef down south before refining his skills here in Chicago.

The Gulfport was a non-nondescript little restaurant with authentic southern artifacts on the wall and some of the best jazz and blues playing on the stereo system.

Yes the music influenced me too even though as young person I was not really into jazz and blues that much but the music from this joint and my mother’s jazz influence came in handy when I finally appreciated jazz in college.
But it was all about the food at Gulfport, Chef Taylor put his foot into each and every dish. Hell he could have made a dish with his foot in the pot and it still would have been good.

Never before or since have I ever seen a place make authentic jambalaya with sauce on the side. And man that sauce was fire, he would warn you about the heat of it yet bring a gravy boat full of it. My late father once drowned his jambalaya in that high heat gravy and ate he it and screamed like a cat in heat.

I’m still looking for someone who made lobster bisque like his, man it had heat, came to the table bright red like the devil’s sweat but was not burning, just flowing with flavor.

He had garlic toast sent to every table, just little pieces of garlic bread that had kissed the toaster and had the right crust and nothing like any kind of garlic or toast you had ever tasted.

The flavor in the food was pure love there (never had a bad meal), the people were great, it was the kind of place that people talked about. He was always written up in the Chicago Sun Times, Tribune and in Ebony magazine.
And I grew up down the street from it.

I went to high school (Brother Rice), and my guidance counselor (former Tinley Park mayor Ed Zabrocki), looked at my home address and said “You live by the Gulfport restaurant, I love that place”.

But all good things must end and by the time I graduated high school, the Gulfport closed in 1994. To my recollection it never went down in quality but the area changed, southern/Cajun was no longer trendy. Though for some of us it was never trendy, it was dinner.

Since then its been Geno's Place (which does have some southern food), and that's what pictured.

Regardless, things change and the nearest authentic Cajun restaurant (The Maple Tree Inn), in Beverly was now growing. I once heard Chef Taylor was there for a while and I also heard he had a place in south suburban Country Club Hills, but never couldn’t verify either story.

Still I will never forget the 11 years my old neighborhood was Cajun Central and the man who lead it, taught us all so much and fed us really well.

